Semantic similarity

Semantic similarity measures have been proposed for comparing concepts within an ontology Schlicker et al., 2006. We therefore treat the NCBI taxonomy as an ontology, and compute semantic similarity between signatures.

onto <- BugSigDBStats::getNcbiTaxonomyObo()

We add the corresponding ID prefix:

dat <- bugsigdbr::importBugSigDB()
dat[["Body site"]] <- tolower(dat[["Body site"]])
dat.feces <- subset(dat, `Body site` == "feces")
ind <- lengths(dat.feces[["NCBI Taxonomy IDs"]]) > 4
dat.feces.5 <- dat.feces[ind,]
sigs <- bugsigdbr::getSignatures(dat.feces.5, tax.id.type = "ncbi")

We remove taxa that are not in the NCBI Taxonomy:

sigs <- BugSigDBStats::syncWithNCBI(sigs, onto)

Now, we compute pairwise semantic similarity for all signatures (which is reasonably fast btw):

system.time(

Given the matrix of pairwise semantic similarity between signatures, we can also compute the semantic similarity of a group of signatures by eg. taking the average similarity between all pairs of signatures.

Here, we compute the semantic similarity of all colorectal cancer signatures in the database for which abundance is increased in the cases.

ind <- !is.na(dat.feces.5[["Condition"]]) &
       dat.feces.5[["Condition"]] == "colorectal cancer" & 
       dat.feces.5[["Body site"]] == "feces" & 
       dat.feces.5[["Abundance in Group 1"]] == "increased"
sum(ind)
## [1] 11
ontologySimilarity::get_sim(sim.mat, group = which(ind))
## [1] 0.5701859

Furthermore, we can compute a p-value for assessing the statistical significance of the similiarity of a group of signatures. The p-value is calculated by random sampling of groups of the same size as group, and calculating how many random groups have at least as great group similarity than does group.

ontologySimilarity::get_sim_p(sim.mat, group = which(ind))
## [1] 0.04400956

Cluster similarity and visualize signature:

EnrichmentPlotter::treeSimPlot(sigs[ind], sim.mat[ind,ind])

Weighted meta-signatures

Weighted semantic similarity

Obtain weighted meta-signatures for body sites:

bs.meta.sigs <- bugsigdbr::getMetaSignatures(dat, column = "Body site")

Calculate weighted semantic similarity between between meta-signatures:

ic <- ontologySimilarity::descendants_IC(onto)
spl <- bs.meta.sigs
.syncWithNCBI2 <- function(spl, onto)
{
    for(i in seq_along(spl)) names(spl[[i]]) <- paste0("NCBITaxon:", names(spl[[i]]))
    utax <- unique(names(unlist(spl)))
    nt <- utax[!(utax %in% onto$id)]
    spl <- lapply(spl, function(s) s[setdiff(names(s), nt)])
    return(spl)
}
spl <- .syncWithNCBI2(spl, onto) 
.wsm <- function(x) BugSigDBStats::weightedBMA(onto, ic, 
                                               names(spl[[x[1]]]), names(spl[[x[2]]]),
                                               unname(spl[[x[1]]]), unname(spl[[x[2]]]))

.getAdjMat <- function(spl, func)
{ 
    combs <- combn(names(spl), 2)
    wsm.bs <- apply(combs, 2, func)
    wsm.df <- data.frame(c1 = combs[1,], c2 = combs[2,], wsm = wsm.bs)
    ig <- igraph::graph_from_data_frame(wsm.df, directed = FALSE)
    adjm <- igraph::get.adjacency(ig, attr = "wsm", sparse = FALSE)
    diag(adjm) <- 1
    return(adjm)
}

adjm <- .getAdjMat(spl, .wsm)
adjm[1:5,1:5]
##                   blood    breast buccal mucosa    caecum     colon
## blood         1.0000000 0.6046227     0.6977796 0.6753457 0.7261330
## breast        0.6046227 1.0000000     0.5492520 0.4521133 0.5558178
## buccal mucosa 0.6977796 0.5492520     1.0000000 0.6439389 0.7240121
## caecum        0.6753457 0.4521133     0.6439389 1.0000000 0.7401935
## colon         0.7261330 0.5558178     0.7240121 0.7401935 1.0000000
wbsp <- EnrichmentPlotter::treeSimPlot(spl, adjm)
wbsp

Rank-biased overlap (RBO)

Rank-biased overlap (RBO) is a measure for the similarity of two potentially incomplete rankings that handles non-conjointness, weighs high ranks more heavily than low ranks, and is monotonic with increasing depth of evaluation.

As explained in this excellent post, RBO thus resolves some of the drawbacks that would be encountered when applying traditional rank-based correlation (eg. Spearman or Kendall) that work best for conjoint rankings.

There are (at least) two existing and somewhat plausible implementations of RBO:

  1. An R implementation in the gespeR package,
  2. A Python implementation in this rbo github repo.

Here, we try out both of them for genus-level meta-signatures for body sites and conditions.

# importing python package from https://github.com/changyaochen/rbo via reticulate
rbo <- reticulate::import("rbo")

Obtain weighted meta-signatures for body sites harmonized to genus level:

bs.meta.sigs.genus <- bugsigdbr::getMetaSignatures(dat,
                                             column = "Body site",
                                             tax.id.type = "taxname",
                                             tax.level = "genus",
                                             exact.tax.level = FALSE)

Apply both RBO implementations for all body-site combinations, and check for agreement in results:

combs <- combn(names(bs.meta.sigs.genus), 2)
rrbo <- function(x) gespeR::rbo(bs.meta.sigs.genus[[x[1]]], 
                                bs.meta.sigs.genus[[x[2]]], 
                                p = 1)
pyrbo <- function(x) rbo$RankingSimilarity(
                        names(bs.meta.sigs.genus[[x[1]]]), 
                        names(bs.meta.sigs.genus[[x[2]]]))$rbo() 
rrbo.bs <- apply(combs, 2, rrbo)
pyrbo.bs <- apply(combs, 2, pyrbo)
cor(rrbo.bs, pyrbo.bs)
## [1] 0.8112021

adjm <- .getAdjMat(bs.meta.sigs.genus, rrbo)
